  "metadata": {
    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "targeted_sweep6_econ_override",
    "description": "Maps the economic override threshold for ideologically stubborn pools. Completes \u00a74.3.3 and fills Table 5's ideology threshold row.\nBACKGROUND: targeted_sweep6_pool_ideology_full (n=20, econ=0.78 fixed) established the diagonal threshold: ideology \u00d7 max_loss \u2273 0.16\u20130.20 allows committed v26 pools to survive economic pressure at econ=0.78. Six cells showed v26 surviving:\n\n  ideology=0.4, max_loss=0.45 (product=0.18) \u2192 v26 holds\n  ideology=0.6, max_loss=0.35 (product=0.21) \u2192 v26 holds\n  ideology=0.6, max_loss=0.45 (product=0.27) \u2192 v26 holds\n  ideology=0.8, max_loss=0.25 (product=0.20) \u2192 v26 holds\n  ideology=0.8, max_loss=0.35 (product=0.28) \u2192 v26 holds\n  ideology=0.8, max_loss=0.45 (product=0.36) \u2192 v26 holds\n\nThe econ_committed_2016_grid and targeted_sweep1 both show v27 winning universally at econ=0.82 with standard ideology params (product\u22480.13). But that was with ideology_strength=0.51, max_loss_pct=0.26 \u2014 well below the diagonal threshold.\nThe critical open question for the paper: does the ~0.82 economic override threshold shift upward when ideology \u00d7 max_loss is high? If ideology=0.8, max_loss=0.45 (product=0.36) allows v26 pools to hold even at econ=0.82, then the boundary in the full 4D parameter space is not a simple threshold \u2014 it is a surface where the required economic majority increases with pool ideology resilience.\nRESEARCH QUESTION: At what economic_split does v27 win unconditionally \u2014 even the most ideologically stubborn committed v26 pools (product=0.36) are forced to capitulate? Is the unconditional override at ~0.82 (as the coarse grid suggests) or does it sit higher, implying that real-world pools with extreme ideology could sustain a minority chain even against very strong economic majorities?\nDESIGN: 3\u00d73\u00d73 grid: ideology=[0.4, 0.6, 0.8] \u00d7 max_loss=[0.25, 0.35, 0.45] \u00d7 econ=[0.82, 0.90, 0.95] This covers the upper-right quadrant of sweep6_full (products 0.10\u20130.36) and sweeps econ upward from the expected override boundary. Reference data at econ=0.78 comes from sweep6_full and does not need to be re-run.\nKey cells to watch:\n  - ideology=0.8, max_loss=0.45, econ=0.82 (product=0.36): does the most resistant\n    pool configuration hold at the nominal override threshold?\n  - The first econ level where all 9 cells show v27 wins is the true override threshold.\n  - Any v26 cells surviving at econ=0.90+ represent a significant upward revision to\n    Table 5's ideology threshold row.\n\nWHAT TO LOOK FOR:\n  - If all 9 cells show v27 at econ=0.82: ideology does not shift the override threshold.\n    The 0.82 value in Table 5 is confirmed as unconditional.\n  - If some cells show v26 at econ=0.82 but all flip by econ=0.90: override threshold\n    shifts to ~0.88\u20130.90 for max-resilience pools. Update Table 5 with a range.\n  - If v26 cells persist at econ=0.95: the override may require economic_split > 0.95,\n    meaning near-total economic consensus is needed against maximally stubborn pools.\n    This would be the most consequential finding for real-world fork assessment.\n\nRETARGET INTERVAL: 144-block (consistent with sweep6_pool_ideology_full for direct comparison). If v26 cells persist at high econ, consider a 2016-block follow-on to determine whether slower retarget further protects ideologically committed pools.\nPARALLELIZATION: 27 scenarios. Recommended: 9 namespaces \u00d7 3 scenarios each (one namespace per ideology_strength value at each max_loss_pct, running 3 econ levels sequentially). Wall-clock: 3 \u00d7 13,000s \u2248 10.8h per namespace (all 9 finish simultaneously).\nAlternatively: 27 namespaces \u00d7 1 scenario = 13,000s \u2248 3.6h (maximum parallelism).\nRun command (27-namespace full parallel, 144-block):\n  for i in $(seq -w 0 26); do\n    kubectl create namespace s6ov-$i\n  done\n  python tools/sweep/3_run_sweep.py \\\n    --input tools/sweep/targeted_sweep6_econ_override/build_manifest.json \\\n    --all-scenarios \\\n    --namespace-prefix s6ov \\\n    --results-dir targeted_sweep6_econ_override/results \\\n    --duration 13000 --retarget-interval 144 --interval 2\n\nOr 9-namespace split (group by ideology_strength):\n  for ns in s6ov-id0 s6ov-id1 s6ov-id2; do\n    kubectl create namespace $ns\n  done\n  # ideology=0.4 (sweep_0000..0008)\n  python tools/sweep/3_run_sweep.py \\\n    --input tools/sweep/targeted_sweep6_econ_override/build_manifest.json \\\n    --scenarios sweep_0000 sweep_0001 sweep_0002 sweep_0003 sweep_0004 sweep_0005 \\\n                sweep_0006 sweep_0007 sweep_0008 \\\n    --namespace s6ov-id0 \\\n    --results-dir targeted_sweep6_econ_override/results \\\n    --duration 13000 --retarget-interval 144 --interval 2 &\n  # (repeat for ideology=0.6 \u2192 s6ov-id1, ideology=0.8 \u2192 s6ov-id2)\n\nCONNECTING TO PHASE 2: Combined with sweep6_pool_ideology_full (econ=0.78 reference), this gives a 4-level econ axis {0.78, 0.82, 0.90, 0.95} across the high-ideology parameter region. The logistic regression boundary fit in \u00a74.8.1 needs this data to correctly parameterize the ideology \u00d7 econ interaction term (\u03b2\u2085 in the model). Without it, the boundary fit will linearly extrapolate past the tested range and likely underestimate the override threshold for high-ideology pools.\n",
